<br>
1. It was structured on a more logical (read: less D&amp;D) system of alignment. Rifts, with its spectrum of alignments from good to evil without devotion to order even being a factor, would be a good example. Or...<br>
<br>
2. Alignment is a personal decision (no stereotypical limits) that primarily affects faction. So, if you're a High Elf, and you choose Chaotic Evil for your alignment, your faction in Felwithe and Kelethin is immediately ruined (threatening or worse), severely damaged in good cities, and only slightly improved in evil cities. In this way, characters who want to choose a variant path get the full experience of being an outcast. An LG Dark Elf necromancer, for instance, is immediately thrown out of Neriak and still can't easily get into Freeport. The faction penalties could be made even worse if you were to worship a god and then pick an alignment antithetical to him. In such cases, you might find yourself unable to train for some time until you repair your faction. In order for this to work, however, there'd need to be more neutral merchants and bankers. Perhaps a certain city (High Pass?) could be designated as neutral ground, or perhaps other cities could be modified to do this. Or...<br>
<br>
3. Alignment exists but has no effect on the game, other than as a personal reminder of your beliefs. By default, if you have /roleplay on, you get a warning before doing anything that would stereotypically violate your alignment -- such as grouping with evils if you're a Paladin, for instance.<br>
<br>
EDIT: Ah, I almost forgot the most important part of this. If alignment is put back in in any fashion, /consider should work appropriately. Good characters conning evil characters should get &quot;dubious,&quot; conning neutrals should get &quot;indifferent,&quot; and conning other goods should get &quot;amiable.&quot; That way alignment, if not stereotyped, will be detectable by the player. It actually works well with the IC element of /consider.<br>
<br>
My major complaint with the alignment system, which was my primary reason for not coming back to EQ when this server was first launched, was that, as it was written, it was a needlessly vicious restriction on RP with little IC justification. However, I have no problem with a new alignment system -- even one similar to the old -- if it works in a manner that permits atypical RP, so long as such RP comes with appropriate consequences. Mostly, I just want there not to *be* stereotyped limits on what a person can do; if someone wants to play an evil High Elf mastermind, a bloodthirsty Human Druid, or a reforming Dark Elf rogue, he should be able to do so without the game system getting in the way. <p>Illudin Arbitrator &lt;Society of Adventurers&gt;<br>
