As far as preserving FV's health as a true RP server, I'd nuke TLC and the no no-drop rules and put back all the ones that were taken out before. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=decius1>Decius1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 26<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/17/02 2:19:19 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2563.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Alignment and considering</span><hr size=1> I'd like Verant to bring alignement into the game a bit more. However, I hate it when dark elves refuse to listen to me because I'm not a dark elf because I roleplay a different alignement system to usual (plus it's amazing how many people forget that there is such an alignement as neutral and just assume that if you're not a darkie you must be good grrr /rant off).<br>
<br>
Anyway, my ideal system is this:<br>
<br>
You are able to alter how you con to people, and how they con to you. So, if you don't like gnomes, you can set it so that everytime a gnome cons you he gets the &quot;looks at you dubiously&quot; message and vica versa. And if you set it at &quot;scowls at you, ready to attack&quot; then you coudn't group with them. This fulfills three roles:<br>
<br>
1) It allows you to enforce alignement restrictions<br>
2) It allows you not to enforce alignement restrictions, or to enforce them differently than usual.<br>
3) It allows you to actually tell whether the human over there is going to /rude you or group with you.<br>
<br>
The roleplaying purist might regard option 3) as cheating, but in my opinion it would greatly facilitate roleplaying rather than hinder it.<br>
